<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Transport select committee submission.docx</title></head><body style="background:#ffffff"><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Written evidence from British Cycling (CYS0143)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.39pt; padding-left:4.61pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cycling is safe but needs to be made safer and to look safer, if we are to reach the type of continental levels of cycling sought by the Prime Minister. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.39pt; padding-left:4.61pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Two million adults are now </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cycling once a week.  We know there are at least 2.75 million more people who want to cycle more but their primary concern is around the perceived lack of safety on the road.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.39pt; padding-left:4.61pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">British Cycling played a leading role in developing the Times newspaper’s 8-poin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">t ‘Cities fit for cycling’ manifesto and the parliamentary ‘Get Britain Cycling’ inquiry. British Cycling strongly endorse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the 18 recommendations of the ‘Get Britain Cycling’ inquiry which sets out </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> action plan for more and safer cycling.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.39pt; padding-left:4.61pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Improving saf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ety is about reducing the risk at source</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> therefore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to improve cycle safety British Cycling recommends</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the following:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> giving local authorities the tools to design roads and junctions with cycling in mind, reducing the risk from HGVs, mak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> it easier to r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">educe speed limits, improv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the enforcement of traffic laws, adding cycle safety to the driving test, strengthening the cycle safety provisions of the Highway Code, improv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> public awareness of cycle safety and mak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> cycle training available to all.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.39pt; padding-left:4.61pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">o facilitate these actions it is vital that there is consistent political leadership and meaningful levels of funding to plan for cycling as a serious transport solution.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.39pt; padding-left:4.61pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">British Cycling is the national governing body for cycling as recognis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ed by the UCI – the international federation for the sport.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.39pt; padding-left:4.61pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">British Cycling works across all levels and six disciplines of the sport (BMX, Mountain Bike, Cyclo-Cross, Road, Track and Cycle Speedway), from providing the support and encouragement people nee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">d to get riding their bikes for the first time, to being home to the hugely successful Great Britain Cycling Team.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.39pt; padding-left:4.61pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Continued success at the highest level is inspiring a boom in participation across the nation. There have never been more opportunities to r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ide a bike, be it for fun or sport and British Cycling is at the heart of this growth. British Cycling also works hard to represent cyclists’ interests at all levels, including campaigning on important issues including road safety.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.39pt; padding-left:4.61pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">As a membership </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">organisation, British Cycling provides a suite of benefits and support to its members, with all membership revenue invested back into cycling.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The breadth of British Cycling’s work is testimony to its status as the only organisation that works across all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">levels of cycling – from the playground to the podium. Whether people are looking to get on a bike for the first time, wanting to find great places to ride, seeking to enter a sportive or race, or needing tips from the pros on riding safely and keeping the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ir bike in top shape, British Cycling is with them every step of the way.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">More than two million adults in England are now riding bikes at least once a week according to the latest results of Sport England’s Active People Survey. Cycling is now the third m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ost popular sport in England. The news also means that British Cycling has achieved its 2013/14 Sport England participation targets.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The most recent results show the increase in cycling from April to October 2013 was 137,000 - which is over three times mo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">re than during the same period in 2012.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Most of the increased demand for cycling has come from people doing recreational cycling, road cycling, and mountain biking. Over the last six months, British Cycling’s work to increase participation in the sport ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s delivered the following: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:none">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">17 Sky Rides in partnership with our principal partner Sky (city centre, traffic-free rides) attracting over 100,000 people.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:none">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">1,800 local guided rides to help people get to know their local routes and gain confidence to ride reg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ularly.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:none">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A 20% growth in competitive events.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:none">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A 29% growth in personal challenge events, known as sportives.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:none">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">47,000 more young people engaged in quality coaching experiences in our network of Go-Ride Clubs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:none">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Membership of British Cycling surpassing 85,000 for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the first time in the organisation’s history.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:none">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Partnerships with over 60 local authorities which support our work to provide more opportunities to ride and race this year.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The results also show there are some challenges to be tackled. British Cycling earl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ier this year launched a strategy to tackle the historical gender imbalance in the sport with the ambition of inspiring one million more women to get on their bikes. Results this year include: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:none">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Over 100,000 women joining our programmes, from taking part i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">n recreational rides through our Breeze network to more women and girls getting involved in racing and clubs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-17.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:none">●</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A 24% increase in the number of women racing in formal cycle sport events.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Continued perceptions about cycling being an unsafe activity are also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">having a knock-on effect in preventing people from getting on bikes. While cycling is as safe as walking, our annual cycling research results show that around 900,000 women would like to take up cycling but are being prevented from doing so because of safe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ty fears.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A lack of confidence to cycle on the roads and not knowing about routes is also a major barrier. British Cycling’s Sky Ride and female-only Breeze programmes aim to allay fears about getting on a bike and can provide people with all the support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">they need.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Is cycling safe?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><a name="h.wubd6m1ila76"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cycling is a safe activity. Importantly, the health benefits of cycling significantly outweigh the risks of having a road traffic accident by a factor of at least 20:1. This factor is even greater in countries with a far bette</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">r road safety record than the UK. Therefore, even in the current conditions, it is in the public interest to have more cycling and not to pursue actions that may limit opportunities for people to cycle.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">More</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">safer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> cycling go hand in hand. The safe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">st place in the world to cycle is the Netherlands where 27% of all journeys are taken by bike. Between 1985 and 2005 it witnessed a 45% increase in cycling and a 58% decrease in cyclist fatalities. The New York City Transport Department has developed hundr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">eds of miles of segregated bike lanes which has led to a 250% increase in four years and a 73% reduction in accidents in just seven years. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><a name="h.da36f3l1nq47"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In the UK, although more than two million people cycle once a week this growth is not translating to growth in util</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ity cycling at a national level. The growth has come from leisure cycling which often takes place in off road sites, quiet roads or even closed roads.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="h.hsfdltxzwa5g"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><a name="h.qew9bflw37lb"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">British Cycling’s insight into the cycling market shows that there are an estimated 2.75 million people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">who actively want to cycle but do not currently. 59% agree with the statement, ‘I am not confident about riding in traffic’ and 55% agree with the statement, ‘I worry about having an accident on the road’. The most common factors (67%) cited for what would</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> make people cycle more is related to better infrastructure.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="h.gjdgxs"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">This attitude is very different from one in our recent history. Cycling levels were at 15% in the 1950s – significantly, the period when we designed cycling out of many of our roads and junction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s. Now just 2% of trips are made by bike. These are made by people who are confident about cycling in traffic. British Cycling is working to target the majority of the population who would cycle if roads were designed with cycling in mind</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> giv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> people ti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">me and space </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">away </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">from motor traffic.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">What central and local Government could do to improve cycling safety?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">British Cycling recommends </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">action is taken in the following areas:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Cycle-proofing: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Roads and junctions should be built with cycling in mind.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> We need to create safe, direct, coherent and desirable conditions for cycling. This requires a coordinated response from government and stakeholders to ensure relevant legislation, policy and guidance works to accommodate people on bikes. As a start, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">government should urgently update traffic sign regulations to allow local authorities to develop safe junctions for cycling and continuous routes to give people confidence. This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">should allow features like,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ‘cycle only traffic lights’, ‘parallel pedestrian </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cycling crossing points’ and ‘Dutch-style roundabouts’. This should be backed by national design standards to ensure continuity and consistency of approach to help all road users.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Meaningful and consistent levels of investment for infrastructure: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> from both the UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and abroad </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">has shown that increasing cycling levels is best achieved through sustained expenditure on cycling programmes at a level of £10 per head or more. This level of investment is required to adapt streets to meet needs of all road u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">sers. This is based on experiences from the UK and abroad. For example, the Cycling Demonstration Towns doubled levels of cycling on £14 to £17 per head and the Mayor of London plans to spend £18 per head. The Netherlands currently spends over £24 per head</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The current level of funding for cycling from the government is about £2 per head of population and is only committed over two years which is inadequate to make a step change in cycling levels. On the other hand, the government has set out £27 billion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">worth of spending on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">roads up to the year 2021 which is the equivalent to £75 per head of population every year. If cycling is important to government then it should have meaningful and consistent levels of investment. This can be achieved by allocating a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">proportion of the existing transport budget in line with local authorities’ ambitions for cycling in their areas.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Reducing the risk from HGVs: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Heavy Goods Vehicles (HGVs) pose a significant risk to people on bikes and other vulnerable road users. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">government should support efforts to improve driver visibility by improving cab design. Loopholes in regulations that allow vehicles not fit blind-spot reducing mirrors and side-guards should be closed. Existing restrictions on HGV movements should be revi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ewed, including how they could be used to improve real perceived safety. Driver CPC training should also be updated to include a mandatory cycle awareness element.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Reducing speed limits saves lives of all road users: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Reducing speed limits is simply the mo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">st effective way of improving safety for all road users. Now is the time to introduce 20mph as the default national speed limit on urban and residential roads with a positive decision at local level needed to increase a limit to 30mph.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Improving the justi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ce system to protect and support vulnerable road users: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Better justice and enforcement is a key element of improving cycle safety. It is clear that the current justice system does not treat bad driving seriously enough despite the impact it causes. Better </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">enforcement of existing traffic laws (prioritising those that have the greatest impact on safety), such as the MET Police’s operation ‘Safeway’, reassure the public and benefit vulnerable road users. There may be a case to devolve certain enforcement power</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s (relating to Advance Stop Lines, mobile phones, speed) to local authorities who may be more incentivised to enforce them.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Adding cycling safety to the driving test: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">All new drivers should be tested on their ability and knowledge of how to drive safely n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ear people on bikes. At present, candidates are not guaranteed to be tested on this knowledge in either the practical or theory test.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Road and Cycle Safety Awareness: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">British Cycling’s aim is to foster a culture of mutual respect between all road users by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> creating a system which encourages us to look out for each other. A government-backed nationwide mutual respect campaign with the aim of improving the understanding and awareness of people sharing the road on bikes and in motor vehicles.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Cycle training m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ade available to all children: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Bikeability is currently only available to 50% of children. Cycling is a life skill and all children should have the opportunity to learn how to ride on the road. Making cycle training part of the national curriculum will giv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e all children this opportunity.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Consistent political leadership for cycling: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">All nations and cities that have achieved the greatest success in developing cycling have a common thread binding them. They have all had politicians at the highest levels make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">an explicit and genuine commitment to make cycling a serious form of transport. National and local government must set out a long-term cycling action plans with measurable targets so that we can plan and track success. Senior officials must be given respon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">sibility for developing cycling to allow continuity of planning and researching issues. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>